4. Cryptography and NIST Cybersecurity Framework Control Families

Cryptography

  • Cryptography is a branch of mathematics based on the transformation of data.
  • Has become indispensable and essential to all aspects of digital life!
  • Provides a solution by protecting data when the data is no longer in the control of the originator (for example when being transmitted over a network or through other systems that are not under the control of the information owner)
  • Applications of Cryptography include:
    • Verifying Integrity
      • can be used to detect modifications to information
    • Verifying Identity
      • Digital Signatures
    • User Authentication (used for both protecting and verifying credentials)
    • Securing Remote Access to Information

Any protection provided using encryption is completely dependent on the security of other components of an information system in order to prevent compromise.

  • Unintended/unauthorized access to information before or after encryption
  • Protection of keys for symmetric and asymmetric encryption (ensuring encryption keys themselves are kept secure)
    • Need for key management systems (KMS) and public key infrastructures (PKI)
      • The support for the binding between a key and its owner is generally referred to as a public key infrastructure
      • The KMS is used to obtain public keys electronically with a high degree of confidence in their integrity and binding to individual
      • Other required functionality:
        • Ability to enter users in and out of the community of key holders
        • Generate keys (or have them generated on their behalf)
        • Disseminate public keys
        • Revoke (invalidate) keys
        • Change keys
  • Using an adequately secure encryption method
    • Strong enough encryption while not needlessly increasing costs or computation requirements, or using weak or vulnerable encryption algorithms
  • Legal and regulatory hurdles
    • Technology export limitation laws
    • Backdoor/access requirements and demands from law enforcement and governments, etc.

Encryption Types

In general, there are a few types of encryption available:

  • Symmetric (private-key encryption)
    • The same key is used for encrypting and decrypting data
      • If used to share information, requires shared secret between sender and recipient
    • Example: AES (as a NIST standard for "military-grade" encryption)
  • Asymmetric (public-key encryption)
    • A public and private key pair is calculated
      • Anything encrypted using one key can be decrypted using the other
      • Public key is "public" (not a secret) and can be widely shared
      • Recipients can decrypt anything that is encrypted using the private key
        • can be used to verify the identity of the sender or the integrity of the information
      • Sender can use the recipients public-key to encrypt information
        • Only the party in possession of the private key can decrypt the information
    • Example algorithms:
      • Diffie-Hellman (1976)
      • RSA (1977)
      • Elliptic-Curve or ECC (1985)
      • El Gamal (1985)
      • DSA (1991)
    • Public-key algorithms may be vulnerable to future quantum computing advances
      • Current 2048 and 4096 bit are considered to be safe for a very long time (unless there is a sudden and unexpected break-through in quantum computing)
      • NIST is already working on standardizing "quantum-resistant" algorithms
        • See announcements and latest updates such as:
          • 2022: NIST Announces First Four Quantum-Resistant Cryptographic Algorithms
          • 2024: NIST Releases First 3 Finalized Post-Quantum Encryption Standards
  • Homomorphic encryption
    • Allows computations to be performed on encrypted data without first having to decrypt it
      • Homomorphic computations on encrypted data will result in an encrypted form that is identical to having the data decrypted and then re-encrypted
      • Eliminates the need for processing data in the clear
    • As of 2017 there is an industry effort for open Homomorphic Encryption Standardization (see Homomorphic Encryption Standardization Consortium)
    • as of 2024 there are many ongoing efforts and whitepapers, however, I am unaware of any widely available implementations in current IT systems

Cryptographic Modules

NIST defines a cryptographic module as "The set of hardware, software, and/or firmware that implements security functions (including cryptographic algorithms), holds plaintext keys and uses them for performing cryptographic operations, and is contained within a cryptographic module boundary."

It is essentially combination of software, firmware and underlying hardware that contains the encryption algorithm, the keys, and also tamper checks and validations for extra hardening. These modules are quite common and range from small hardware security modules (HSM) build into smart phones SOC to TPM SOC build into client and server system boards, to dedicated large-scale enterprise/military grade rack-mounted hardware.

Network Encryption

  • Link encryption
    • The link layer is encrypted
    • must use special equipment (since routing data is also encrypted)
  • End-to-end encryption
    • higher layer communications (such as layer 4 and above) are encrypted, therefore IP routing data is visible
    • Can be deployed over standard networks and routed over the Internet

Control Families

NIST Cybersecurity Framework provides a standard set of "Control Families" and recommends a set of controls so practitioners and auditors can assess compliance based on standardized terminology. NIST SP800-53 Rev.5 specifies 20 categories of "control families" containing 1189 "controls".
The 20 categories are:

  • Access Control (AC)
    • Physical and logical access controls
    • Logical access controls can be internally built in the Operating Systems or application, or can be reinforced using security packages and add-ons.
    • Responsibilities:
      • limit system access to authorized users only
      • control processes acting on behalf of authorized users
      • limit and control devices, including other systems (access control for other systems and machines)
      • limit and control types of transactions and functions that authorized users are permitted to exercise
  • Awareness and Training (AT)
    • Making system users aware of their security responsibilities
    • Teaching them correct practices
    • Supports individual accountability
    • Responsibilities:
      • Ensure that managers and users of organizational systems are made aware of the security risks associated with their activities and of the applicable laws, executive orders, directives, policies, standards, instructions, regulations, or procedures related to the security of organizational systems
      • Ensure that organizational personnel are adequately trained to carry out their assigned information security-related duties and responsibilities
  • Audit and Accountability (AU)
    • Audit: "is an independent review and examination of records and activities to assess the adequacy of system controls and ensure compliance with established policies and operational procedures"
    • Audit trail: simply means records of who did what and when
      • can assist in detecting security violations, performance issues, and flaws in applications
    • Responsibilities:
      • create, protect, and retain system audit records to the extent needed to enable the monitoring, analysis, investigation, and reporting of unlawful, unauthorized, or inappropriate system activity
      • ensure that the actions of individual system users can be uniquely traced to those users so they can be held accountable
  • Assessment, Authorization, and Monitoring (CA)
    • Assessment of the security controls is done on a continuous basis
    • Support a near real-time analysis of the organization’s current security posture
    • Responsibilities:
      • periodically assess the security controls in organizational systems to determine if the controls are effective in their application
      • develop and implement plans of action designed to correct deficiencies and reduce or eliminate vulnerabilities in organizational systems
      • authorize the operation of organizational systems and any associated system connections
      • monitor security controls on an ongoing basis to ensure the continued effectiveness of the controls
  • Configuration Management (CM)
    • Examples: baseline configuration, configuration change control, security impact analysis, least functionality, and software usage restrictions (Remember "AWS Config"?)
    • Responsibilities:
      • establish and maintain baseline configurations and inventories of organizational systems, including hardware, software, firmware, and documentation throughout the respective SDLC (system development life cycle)
      • establish and enforce security configuration settings for information technology products employed in organizational systems
  • Contingency Planning (CP)
    • Contingency: an event with the potential to disrupt system operations, thereby disrupting critical mission and business functions
    • Examples: power outage, hardware failure, fire, or storm, or "disasters"
    • Contingency planning is to plan for minimizing impact in case of a contingency and produces:
      • System Contingency Plan (SCP)
      • Continuity of Operations Plan (COOP) or Business Continuity Plan (BCP)
      • Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)
      • Examples of implementations:
        • Offsite backup in the event of data loss due to a catastrophic event (SCP)
        • Having an alternative payment processing at a store in case of payment terminal failure (Business Continuity plan)
        • detailed and tested plans and procedures to restore a failed system using backup-restore, multi-site clusters, Active-standby systems, etc (DPR)
      • Contingency planning controls include: contingency plan, contingency training, contingency plan testing, system backup, and system recovery and reconstitution
      • Responsibilities:
        • establish, maintain, and effectively implement plans for emergency response
        • backup operations
        • oversee post-disaster recovery for organizational systems to ensure the availability of critical information resources and the continuity of operations in emergency situations
  • Identification and Authentication (IA)
    • something you know (password, pin)
    • something you have (security token, smart card, another device)
    • something you are (biometrics)
    • something you do (dynamic biometrics, behavioural analysis)
    • Responsibilities:
      • identify system users, processes acting on behalf of users, or devices
      • authenticate or verify the identities of those users, processes, or devices, as a prerequisite to allowing access to organizational systems
  • Individual Participation (IP)
    • Individual (and user) concerns such as user trust, privacy concerns, and being surveilled by a system may lead to unexpected altered behaviours
      - examples of altered behaviours: deliberately bypassing system security measures and controls, using alternative methods to meet requirements such as fabricating information (remember mouse-movers?), malicious compliance, etc.
    • Responsibilities:
      • request consent for processing PII
      • provide access to PII and redress opportunities for individuals to amend or correct PII
      • provide notice to individuals regarding the processing of PII
  • Incident Response (IR)
    • Developing standards and processes to respond to security incidents
    • can be included as part of the Contingency Planning
    • Examples: incident response training, incident response testing, incident handling, incident monitoring, and incident reporting
    • Responsibilities:
      • establish an operational incident handling capability for organizational systems that includes adequate preparation, detection, analysis, containment, recovery, and user response activities
      • track, document, and report incidents to appropriate organizational officials and/or authorities
  • Maintenance (MA)
    • Corrective maintenance (can be an incident): Maintenance performed outside of a scheduled cycle when a system fails
    • Controlled maintenance: maintenance that is scheduled and performed in accordance with the manufacturer’s specifications
    • Responsibilities:
      • perform periodic and timely maintenance of organizational systems
      • provide effective controls on the tools, techniques, mechanisms, and personnel used to conduct system maintenance
  • Media Protection (MP)
    • Must include controls for all media types: digital, non-digital, and residual information (information that is hidden inside a system or device, for example router configurations that are inside the device flash memory, or information stored inside a network printer, etc.)
    • Restrict access to media and accountability, apply security labels to sensitive information, and provide instructions (procedures and guidelines) on how to remove information from media such that the information cannot be retrieved or reconstructed
    • Examples of media protection controls: media access, media marking, media storage, media transport, and media sanitization.
    • Responsibilities:
      • protect all system media
      • limit access to information on system media to authorized users
      • sanitize or destroy system media before disposal or release for reuse
  • Privacy Authorization (PA)
    • Aids an organization in ensuring that it is only processing PII in ways that it has the authority for and clear purposes for doing so
    • Accountability for following relevant policies, and minimizing potential noncompliance costs (PIPEDA, GDPR, etc.) and reputational damage
    • Responsibilities:
      • identify the legal bases that authorize particular personally identifiable information (PII) collection use, maintenance, and sharing
      • specify in their notices the purpose(s) for which PII is collected
      • manage the sharing of PII with external parties
  • Physical and Environmental Protection (PE)
    • Encompasses all physical security of systems ranging from maintenance (leaky roof) to facilities (heating, AC, etc), access and services (such as power and internet connection)
    • Also includes geographic area and environmental hazards (such as elevation, flood, earthquake, lighting strikes, hot, cold, physical damage, etc.)
    • Can include static structures, mobile, and portable system (anything from a shed to a container to a vehicle, etc.)
    • Responsibilities:
      • Limit physical access to systems, equipment, and the respective operating environments to authorized individuals
      • protect the physical plant and support infrastructure for systems
      • protect systems against environmental hazards
      • provide appropriate environmental controls in facilities containing systems
  • Planning (PL)
    • System planning and design (identifying and planning for specific security needs in planning stages)
    • Enables security design, secure-by-design, trusted development, etc.
    • Responsibilities:
      • Develop, document, periodically update, and implement security plans for organizational systems that describe the security controls in place or planned for the system, as well as the rules of behaviour for individuals accessing the systems
  • Program Management (PM)
    • Having formal processes for information security as a function of the business (with official management) so the system security functions are the result of a planned and integrated management philosophy
    • Responsibilities: business management support
  • Personnel Security (PS)
    • Seeks to minimize the risk that staff (permanent, temporary, or contractor) pose to organizational assets through the malicious use or exploitation of their legitimate access
    • Responsibilities:
      • Ensure that individuals occupying positions of responsibility within organizations (including third-party service providers) are trustworthy and meet established security criteria for those positions
      • Ensure that organizational information and systems are protected during and after personnel actions such as terminations and transfers
      • Employ formal sanctions for personnel failing to comply with organizational security policies and procedures (How can employees be motivated to comply with established policies?).
  • Risk Assessment (RA)
    • Risk Assessment process:
      • Identify relevant threats to organizations or threats directed through organizations against other organizations
      • Identify vulnerabilities both internal and external to organizations
      • Identify impact (i.e., harm) to organizations that may occur given the potential for threats exploiting vulnerabilities
      • Identify the likelihood that harm will occur
    • Responsibilities:
      • Conducting risk assessments and monitoring risk and periodic re-assessments
  • System and Services Acquisition (SA)
    • Examples of controls: allocation of resources, acquisition process, system documentation, supply chain protection, trustworthiness, criticality analysis, developer-provided training, component authenticity, and developer screening
    • Responsibilities:
      • Allocate sufficient resources to protect organizational systems adequately
      • Employ SDLC processes that incorporate information security considerations
      • Employ software usage and installation restrictions
      • Ensure that third-party providers employ adequate security measures to protect information, applications, and/or services outsourced from the organization.
  • System and Communications Protection (SC)
    • To address the confidentiality and integrity of information at rest and in transit
    • It is recommended to separate user functionality and system management (For example have a "management network" for system administrative tasks that is inaccessible to regular users)
    • Examples: application partitioning, denial of service protection, boundary protection, trusted path, mobile code, session authenticity, thin nodes, honeypots, transmission confidentiality and integrity, operations security, protection of information at rest and in transit, and usage restrictions
    • Responsibilities:
      • monitor, control, and protect organizational communications (i.e., information transmitted or received by organizational systems) at the external boundaries and key internal boundaries of the systems
      • employ architectural designs, software development techniques, and systems engineering principles that promote effective information security within organizational systems.
  • Systems and information Integrity (SI)
    • provides assurance that the information being accessed has not been meddled with or damaged by an error in the system
    • Responsibilities:
      • identify, report, and correct information and system flaws in a timely manner
      • provide protection from malicious code at appropriate locations within organizational systems
      • monitor system security alerts and advisories and respond appropriately
